1. Final Project Data Science Hacktiv8 Batch 30¶

Intro to Data Science prepared by Almas Shabrina

About Data

This Data presented about Kickstarter project that has been launched since 1970-01-01 - 2018-01-02 base on dataseet that I've downloaded from https://www.kaggle.com/kemical/kickstarter-projects. Because of Kickstarter is established in 2009 but i found the minumum project launched year is 1970 (by temp_launched.agg("min") is 1970-01-01), therefore, I will only use data from the project deadline time since 2016 - 2017. There will be some slicing and data cleaning process.

Kickstarter is an American public benefit corporation based in Brooklyn, New York, that maintains a global crowdfunding platform focused on creativity. The company's stated mission is to "help bring creative projects to life. Kickstarter launch, on April 28, 2009, 18 million people have backed a project, $4.9 billion has been pledged, and 179,812 projects have been successfully funded.

Topic covered and question to answer from the data:

  1. Which project category has the highest success rate?
  2. What is the average fund collected by all projects?
  3. What is the average fund for a successful project to be funded?
  4. What is the average success rate of a successful project
  5. What is the average project success rate?
  6. Which country has the highest succes rate?
  7. Which country has the most projects?
  8. Is there an corelation on the duration with the amount of funds collected?
  9. Is there a correlation between the duration of the project and the success rate?
  10. Is there a correlation between the amount of funds collected and total backers?
  11. What causes the project to fail?
  12. What causes the project to be successful?

1.1 Data Understanding - Description Columns¶

  1. ID - internal kickstarter id
  2. name - name of project - A project is a finite work with a clear goal that youd like to bring to life. Think albums, books, or films.
  3. category - category
  4. main_category - category of campaign
  5. currency - currency used to support
  6. deadline - deadline for crowdfunding
  7. goal - The funding goal is the amount of money that a creator needs to complete their project.
  8. launched - date launched
  9. pledged - amount pledged by "crowd"
  10. state - Current condition the project is in
  11. backers - number of backers
  12. country - country pledged from
  13. usd_pledged - Pledged amount in USD (conversion made by Kickstater)
  14. usd_pledge_real - Pledged amount in USD (conversion made by fixer.io api)
  15. usd_goal_real - conversion in US dollars of the goal column, Goal amount in USD

Note :

  • H0. Dependent Variable is State
  • H1. Independent Variables are variables other than State

1.3 Data Extracting¶

After knowing what data is available in the dataset, then determine what data we need to get insight. What variables are needed as well as the scope of the data. This Data presented about Kickstarter project that has been launched since 1970-01-01 - 2018-01-02 base on dataseet that I've downloaded. Because of Kickstarter is established in 2009 but i found the minumum project deadline year is 1970 (by df["deadline"].agg("min") is 1970-01-01), therefore, I will only use data from the project launched between 2016 - 2017. There will be some slicing and data cleaning process.

4. Visualization of Correlation¶

This Correlation Tests will check if two variables of more have a linear relationship. For your information

  • The dependent variable for the data used is the state variable.
  • Independent variables for the data used are other than state variables. Like goals, pledged, backers, duration, month, category, country.

The data will use only data with 2 types of status namely successfull and failed, for the status of suspended, live and canceled will not be included in the hypothesis testing this time.

Pearsons Correlation Coefficient Tests whether two samples have a linear relationship.

Assumptions

  • Observations in each sample are independent.
  • Observations in each sample are normally distributed.

Interpretation

  • H0: the two samples are independent.
  • H1: there is a dependency between the samples.

Information about the Pearson correlation coefficient:

  • The Pearson correlation coefficient can take on any real value in the range 1 r 1.
  • The maximum value r = 1 corresponds to the case when theres a perfect positive linear relationship between x and y. In other words, larger x values correspond to larger y values and vice versa.
  • The value r > 0 indicates positive correlation between x and y.
  • The value r = 0 corresponds to the case when x and y are independent.
  • The value r < 0 indicates negative correlation between x and y.
  • The minimal value r = 1 corresponds to the case when theres a perfect negative linear relationship between x and y. In other words, larger x values correspond to smaller y values and vice versa.

Pearson's Correlation test

By using a level of accuracy of 95% then:

if p > 0.05:

print('Probably independent')

else:

print('Probably dependent')

5. Conclusion¶

Project status (dependent variable) is affected or has a correlation with (independent variable):

  1. categories
  2. pledged
  3. duration
  4. backers

1. Category

The more categories go up, the less hope for a successful project to be funded. As in the following data, if goes to left of the x-axis, the opportunity for a successful project to be funded or the success rate is lower. The 3 categories with the highest failed rates are Journalist, Food and Technology

6. Written Suggestions¶

From 4 independent variables that show a correlation with the status of a successful project (dependent variable), it can be concluded that projects that have a greater chance of successful funding are:

  1. Avoid making projects using the categories Journalist, Food and Technology, because the project is 3 categories with the highest failed rate.

  2. We recommend choosing a duration of 20 - 44 days based on the graph above because the projects with that duration are the most numerous and have the highest success rate.

  3. The higher pledged fund has higher chance for project to succeed, it is better to set a pledged fund around 30941 USD or greater, because the fund is an Av fund collected / pledged for successful Project.

  4. The more backers, the higher chance for project to succeed, the campaigner should try to get at least 330 backers, because that number is the average number of backers for successful projects.
